    "content": "<html lang=\"en\">\n<head>\n    <meta charset=\"UTF-8\">\n    <meta name=\"viewport\" content=\"width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0\">\n    <title>Dynamic Typing Demonstration</title>\n    <style>\n        body {\n            font-family: Arial, sans-serif;\n            line-height: 1.6;\n            max-width: 800px;\n            margin: 0 auto;\n            padding: 20px;\n            background-color: #f5f5f5;\n        }\n        h1 {\n            color: #2c3e50;\n            text-align: center;\n        }\n        .demo-container {\n            background-color: white;\n            padding: 20px;\n            border-radius: 5px;\n            box-shadow: 0 2px 5px rgba(0,0,0,0.1);\n            margin-bottom: 20px;\n        }\n        button {\n            background-color: #3498db;\n            color: white;\n            border: none;\n            padding: 8px 16px;\n            border-radius: 4px;\n            cursor: pointer;\n            margin-right: 10px;\n        }\n        button:hover {\n            background-color: #2980b9;\n        }\n        pre {\n            background-color: #f8f8f8;\n            padding: 10px;\n            border-radius: 4px;\n            overflow-x: auto;\n        }\n        .output {\n            margin-top: 20px;\n            padding: 10px;\n            background-color: #e8f4f8;\n            border-left: 4px solid #3498db;\n        }\n    </style>\n</head>\n<body>\n    <h1>Dynamic Typing in JavaScript</h1>\n    \n    <div class=\"demo-container\">\n        <h2>What is Dynamic Typing?</h2>\n        <p>Dynamic typing means that variables can hold values of any type, and their type can change during runtime. Unlike statically-typed languages where you declare a variable's type, JavaScript variables can be reassigned to different types.</p>\n        \n        <h3>Example 1: Variable Type Change</h3>\n        <pre>let dynamicVar = 42;          // Number\ndynamicVar = \"Hello\";       // Now a String\ndynamicVar = true;          // Now a Boolean</pre>\n        \n        <p>Try it out:</p>\n        <button onclick=\"example1()\">Run Example 1</button>\n        <div id=\"output1\" class=\"output\"></div>\n    </div>\n    \n    <div class=\"demo-container\">\n        <h3>Example 2: Type Coercion</h3>\n        <p>JavaScript will automatically convert types in certain operations (called type coercion):</p>\n        <pre>let result = \"5\" + 2;       // \"52\" (string concatenation)\nlet anotherResult = \"5\" - 2;  // 3 (numeric subtraction)</pre>\n        \n        <button onclick=\"example2()\">Run Example 2</button>\n        <div id=\"output2\" class=\"output\"></div>\n    </div>\n    \n    <div class=\"demo-container\">\n        <h3>Example 3: Checking Types</h3>\n        <p>Use <code>typeof</code> to check a variable's current type:</p>\n        <pre>let item = 100;\nconsole.log(typeof item);  // \"number\"\n\nitem = \"Hello\";\nconsole.log(typeof item);  // \"string\"</pre>\n        \n        <button onclick=\"example3()\">Run Example 3</button>\n        <div id=\"output3\" class=\"output\"></div>\n    </div>\n    \n    <div class=\"demo-container\">\n        <h3>Example 4: Loose Equality (==) vs Strict Equality (===)</h3>\n        <p>Loose equality performs type coercion, strict equality doesn't:</p>\n        <pre>\"5\" == 5    // true (type coercion)\n\"5\" === 5   // false (different types)</pre>\n        \n        <button onclick=\"example4()\">Run Example 4</button>\n        <div id=\"output4\" class=\"output\"></div>\n    </div>\n\n    <script>\n        function logToOutput(outputId, message) {\n            const outputElement = document.getElementById(outputId);\n            outputElement.innerHTML += `<div>${message}</div>`;\n        }\n\n        function example1() {\n            const outputId = \"output1\";\n            document.getElementById(outputId).innerHTML = \"\";\n            \n            let dynamicVar = 42;\n            logToOutput(outputId, `Initial value: ${dynamicVar} (type: ${typeof dynamicVar})`);\n            \n            dynamicVar = \"Hello\";\n            logToOutput(outputId, `After reassignment: ${dynamicVar} (type: ${typeof dynamicVar})`);\n            \n            dynamicVar = true;\n            logToOutput(outputId, `After another reassignment: ${dynamicVar} (type: ${typeof dynamicVar})`);\n        }\n\n        function example2() {\n            const outputId = \"output2\";\n            document.getElementById(outputId).innerHTML = \"\";\n            \n            const result = \"5\" + 2;\n            logToOutput(outputId, `\"5\" + 2 = ${result} (type: ${typeof result})`);\n            \n            const anotherResult = \"5\" - 2;\n            logToOutput(outputId, `\"5\" - 2 = ${anotherResult} (type: ${typeof anotherResult})`);\n        }\n\n        function example3() {\n            const outputId = \"output3\";\n            document.getElementById(outputId).innerHTML = \"\";\n            \n            let item = 100;\n            logToOutput(outputId, `Initial type: ${typeof item}`);\n            \n            item = \"Hello\";\n            logToOutput(outputId, `After reassignment, type: ${typeof item}`);\n            \n            item = { name: \"JavaScript\" };\n            logToOutput(outputId, `After another reassignment, type: ${typeof item}`);\n        }\n\n        function example4() {\n            const outputId = \"output4\";\n            document.getElementById(outputId).innerHTML = \"\";\n            \n            logToOutput(outputId, `\"5\" == 5: ${\"5\" == 5} (with type coercion)`);\n            logToOutput(outputId, `\"5\" === 5: ${\"5\" === 5} (strict comparison)`);\n            logToOutput(outputId, `0 == false: ${0 == false} (type coercion)`);\n            logToOutput(outputId, `0 === false: ${0 === false} (strict comparison)`);\n        }\n    </script>\n</body>\n</html>"
